				\begin{document}$$\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {s(i)} \hfill & = \hfill & {\frac{{b(i) - a(i)}}{{{\mathrm{max}}\{ a(i),b(i)\} }}} \hfill \\ {} \hfill & = \hfill & {\left( {\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {1 - a(i){\mathrm{/}}b(i),} \hfill & {{\mathrm{if}}\,{\kern 1pt} a(i) < b(i)} \hfill \\ {0,} \hfill & {{\mathrm{if}}\,{\kern 1pt} a(i) = b(i)} \hfill \\ {b(i){\mathrm{/}}a(i) - 1,} \hfill & {{\mathrm{if}}\,{\kern 1pt} a(i) > b(i)} \hfill \end{array}} \right..} \hfill \end{array}$$\end{document}From this definition it is seen that the silhouette coefficient s is in the range −1 ≤ s ≤ 1. Values near +1 indicate that the sample is far away from the neighbouring cluster and accordingly fits well into its own cluster. A value of 0 indicates that the sample is on or very close to the boundary between its own and the neighbouring cluster, and negative values indicate that it might have been assigned to the wrong cluster. A sorted diagram of all silhouette coefficients can thus be used to visualise the representation quality of a clustering. In addition, the average silhouette coefficient for all samples—usually denoted as silhouette score—can be used to compare the representation quality for different clusterings, e.g., using different Nk values. It hence even provides a single numeric value for solution quality assessment.
